What is a Multi-Container Pod?

A multi-container pod is a Kubernetes pod that runs more than one container inside the same pod.

üëâ All containers in a pod:

Share the same IP address

Share the same network namespace

Can share volumes

Are scheduled together on the same node

Think of it as containers that must live and work together.

Why are multi-container pods used?

They‚Äôre used when containers are tightly coupled and depend on each other.

Common reasons:

1Ô∏è‚É£ One container supports another
2Ô∏è‚É£ They need shared storage
3Ô∏è‚É£ They must communicate via localhost
4Ô∏è‚É£ They should be scaled and deployed together

Common Multi-Container Pod Patterns
1Ô∏è‚É£ Sidecar pattern (most common ‚≠ê)

One main app container + one helper container

Example:

App container ‚Üí writes logs

Sidecar container ‚Üí reads logs and ships them to ELK

App Container  ---> /logs (shared volume)
Sidecar        ---> sends logs

2Ô∏è‚É£ Ambassador pattern

A helper container handles network communication.

Example:

App talks to localhost

Ambassador handles auth / TLS / retries

3Ô∏è‚É£ Adapter pattern

Converts output into a standard format.

Example:

App produces logs in custom format

Adapter converts logs to JSON

Simple YAML Example (Sidecar)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: multi-container-pod
spec:
  volumes:
    - name: shared-logs
      emptyDir: {}
  containers:
    - name: app
      image: nginx
      volumeMounts:
        - name: shared-logs
          mountPath: /var/log/nginx

    - name: sidecar
      image: busybox
      command: ["sh", "-c", "tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log"]
      volumeMounts:
        - name: shared-logs
          mountPath: /var/log/nginx

What‚Äôs happening here?

Nginx writes logs

Sidecar reads logs from the same volume

Both containers share the pod lifecycle

When NOT to use multi-container pods ‚ùå

If containers can run independently

If they need separate scaling

If they don‚Äôt strongly depend on each other

Interview one-liner üéØ

A multi-container pod runs multiple tightly coupled containers that share networking and storage, commonly used for sidecar, ambassador, or adapter patterns.

